**Abstract:**
Major essay titled "Christianity is not a Doctrine" with extensive quotations from Kierkegaard, Charles Taylor, Hans Frei, Levinas, and de Lubac. Develops argument that Christianity was wrongly conceived as doctrine requiring intellectual assent rather than participation in an ongoing drama. Includes extended analysis of Pyrrhonian skepticism, Nietzsche, truth as correspondence, and the primacy of practical over speculative knowledge. Proposes narrative rather than doctrine as proper form for faith.

**AI Recommendation:** Major book chapter; variant of 99-aug-1. Central theoretical text.

